President Donald J. Trump has announced his intention to nominate Caroline A. Crenshaw for the position of Member of the Securities and Exchange Commission. Currently serving as Senior Counsel at the SEC and as a Captain in the United States Army Reserve, Judge Advocate General's Corps, Crenshaw has been with the SEC since 2013. She has worked in various departments within the SEC, focusing on legal and policy analysis related to corporate governance, investment management, enforcement, international regulation, and the oversight of self-regulatory organizations. Prior to joining the SEC, Crenshaw practiced law at Sutherland, Asbill and Brennan LLP, representing public companies, broker-dealers, and investment advisers in securities law investigations and enforcement matters. Crenshaw holds an undergraduate degree from Harvard College and a law degree from the University of Minnesota Law School.